In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in `CreateMauiApp()` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android =>
        {
            android.OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ });
            android.OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ });
        });
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios =>
        {
            ios.DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ });
        });
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.
- `AddAndroid` exposes standard Activity callbacks (`OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnCreate`, etc.).
- `AddiOS` exposes `UIApplicationDelegate` methods (`DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc.).
- All handlers are registered in one place — no need to subclass platform classes.
